function checkValidString(s) {
    let left_balance = 0, right_balance = 0;

    for (let i = 0; i < s.length; i++) {
        left_balance += (s[i] === '(' || s[i] === '*') ? 1 : -1;
        right_balance += (s[s.length - 1 - i] === ')' || s[s.length - 1 - i] === '*') ? 1 : -1;

        if (left_balance < 0 || right_balance < 0)
            return false;
    }

    return true;
}
```


    The algorithm uses the greedy approach by keeping count of the possible balance of left and right parentheses with two variables `left_balance` and `right_balance`. 

We iterate through the string in both forward and reverse direction looking at balance of the parentheses. The '*' character is treated as a left parenthesis when iterating forward, and as a right parenthesis when iterating in reverse. If at any point either balance is negative, we return false, as it is not a valid string.

If we successfully finish the iteration without returning false, it means the string is valid, and we return true.

